Simulating a Blood Parasite (Unvaccinated Population)

Exercise 1:

Write a function to simulate the spread of a blood parasite over 100 time steps across the 21 vertices based on an undirected and unweighted version of the network and record the number of infected individuals at each step.

NUG <- UG
bPUG <- function()
{
  V(NUG)$state <<- 0
  V(NUG)$color <<- "green"
  random <- sample(1:21, size =1)
  V(NUG)$state[random] <<- 1
  V(NUG)$color[random] <<- "red"
  UG <<- NUG
  infectedCount <- c()
  for( i in (1:50))
  {
    V(NUG)$state[intersect(unlist(adjacent_vertices(NUG, which(V(NUG)$state == 1))),  which(V(NUG)$state == 0))] <<-rbinom(length(intersect(unlist(adjacent_vertices(NUG, which(V(NUG)$state == 1))),  which(V(NUG)$state == 0))),1,.413)
    V(NUG)$color[V(NUG)$state == 1] <<-"red"
    infectedCount[i] <- sum(V(NUG)$state == 1)
  }
  return(infectedCount)
}
plot(bPUG())

plot(NUG)

    V(NUG)$color[V(NUG)$state == 1] <<-"red"

Exercise 5:

Write a function to simulate the blood parasite based on an undirected but weighted version of the tuatara network.

bPUG <- function()
{
  V(NUG)$state <- 0
  V(NUG)$color <- "green"
  random <- sample(1:21, size =1)
  V(NUG)$state[random] <- 1
  V(NUG)$color[random] <- "red"
  UG <<- NUG
  infectedCount <- c()
  i <- 1
  count <- 0
  result <- 0
 while(i <= 50 & result < 21)
 {
   for(j in (1:21))
   {
     for(k in(1:21))
     {
       if(are.connected(NUG, j, k))
       {
         if(V(NUG)[j]$state == 1 && V(NUG)[k]$state == 0)
         {
           p <- 0.1 * E(NUG,c(j,k))$weight
           V(NUG)[k]$state <- rbinom(1,1,p)
         }
       }
     }
   }
   result <- sum(V(NUG)$state == 1)
   count <- i
   i<- i+1
  }
  return(count)
}

Exercise 9:

Discuss what effect incorporating contact heterogeneity has on how quickly a blood parasite spreads through a population. Justify your answer numerically.

Based on the 100 simulations from (6), it is obvious that incorporating contact heterogeneity makes the blood parasite to spreads faster (9.5 plus or minus 4.475523 time steps) than without the incorporating contact heterogeneity(10.74 plus or minus 3.119246). On an average, it takes nearly 11 time steps for the blood parasite to spread in an unweighted and undirected tuatare network, whereas it only takes 9.5 time steps for the blood parasite to spread.

Exercise 10:

Discuss what effect incorporating contact directionality has on how quickly a blood parasite spreads through a population. Justify your answer numerically.

Based on the 100 simulations from (9), it is obvious that incorporating contact directionality makes the blood parasite spreads slower (47.44 plus or minus 9.416641 time steps) compared to other simulations we have been looking so far. This makes sense since there are some edges that doesnt have any out degree cannot be affected even after finishing 50 time steps. Therefore, incorporating contact directionality makes the blood parasite spreads slower in the tuatara network.

Simulating a Blood Parasite (Vaccinated Population)

Exercise 11:

Write a function that takes the names of three vertices as arguments, vaccinates them, simulates the spread of a blood parasite over 50 time steps across the remaining 18 vertices based on a directed and weighted version of the tuatara network, and returns the number of infected individuals at each step.

es <- read.csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/zyakaii9vr0al11/e.csv?dl=1")
G <- graph.data.frame(es, vs, directed = T)
NG <- G
bPG <- function(ran, rand, rando)
{
  V(G)$color[ran] <<- "yellow"
  V(G)$color[rand] <<- "yellow"
  V(G)$color[rando] <<- "yellow"
  
  V(NG)$state <<- 0
  V(NG)$color <<- "green"
  
  V(NG)$state[ran] <<- 2
  V(NG)$state[rand] <<- 2
  V(NG)$state[rando] <<- 2
 
  random <- sample((1:21), size = 1)
  while( !ran == random && !rand == random && !rando == random)
  {
    random <- sample((1:21), size = 1)
  }
   V(NG)$state[random] <<- 1
   V(NG)$color[random] <<- "red"
   G <<- NG
   V(G)$color[V(G)$state == 1] <<- "red"
  V(G)$color[V(G)$state == 0] <<- "green"
  infectedCount <- c()
  
  for( i in (1:50))
  {
   for(j in (1:21))
   {
     for(k in(1:21))
     {
       if(are.connected(NG, j, k))
       {
         if(V(NG)[j]$state == 1 && V(NG)[k]$state == 0)
         {
           p <- 0.1 * E(NUG,c(j,k))$weight
           V(NG)[k]$state <<- rbinom(1,1,p)
         }
       }
     }
       }
      
   infectedCount[i] <- sum(V(NG)$state == 1)
  }
  V(NG)$color[V(NG)$state == 1] <<- "red"
    V(NG)$color[V(NG)$state == 0] <<- "green"
    
  return(infectedCount)
  
}

Exercise 13:

Simulate 1000 trials of this Blood Parasite using random vaccination (i.e., randomly select a new set of three tuatara for each trial) and produce a plot of the average number of infected tuatara over time.

count <- c()
for( i in 1:100)
{
list <- c(1:21)
random1 <- sample(x=list, size =1)
list1 <- list[list != random1]
random2 <- sample(x=list1, size = 1)
list2 <- list1[list1 != random2]
random3 <- sample(x=list2, size = 1)
list3 <- list2[list2 != random3]
count[i] <- mean(bPG(random1, random2, random3) )
}
